<DOC><DOCNO> AP890327-0078 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 1234EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Japan-Soviet     03-27 0192</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Japan-Soviet,0198</SECOND><HEAD>Japan TV Employee Will Fly on Soviet Space Station</HEAD><DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A Japanese television network has reached agreementwith Soviet authorities for one of its employees to go aboard theSoviet space station Mir by the end of 1991, a network officialsaid Monday.   The agreement was signed between Kiichi Nakamura, of the TokyoBroadcasting System, Inc., and Oleg Firsyk, vice president ofGlavkosmos, the Soviet commercial space agency, said the official,who refused to be identified.   To mark the network's 40th anniversary, one of its employeeswill be flown to the space station aboard a Soyuz spaceship. Duringthe six-day stay aboard the Mir, live broadcasts of the staffer'sactivities will shown daily in Japan, he said.   The official refused to say how much the broadcaster will paythe Soviets.   Employees at the network are signing up to be considered for theflight. ``Everybody wants to go,'' said one reporter.   The Mir station was launched in 1986 and has a capacity of six.   Three Japanese astronauts are undergoing training in the UnitedStates, and one is scheduled to board a U.S. space shuttle flightby July 1991.</TEXT></DOC>